The paper deals with fair resource allocation problems and distributed algorithms, which are topics that are commonly studied in the Distributed Computing (cs.DC) and Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-categories. The use of network utility maximization problems suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. The algorithm's properties, such as being self-stabilizing and allowing incremental and local adjustments, suggest that it may also be relevant to the Systems and Control (cs.SI) sub-category. Finally, the use of approximation algorithms and convergence guarantees suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
